{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658745"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:54:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:54:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20817"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20817","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20817"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13692"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97366"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13692"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20817"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79981"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"12466"},{"type":"tags","id":"12467"},{"type":"tags","id":"12649"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32974"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32975"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97366"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EInvasive aspergillosis is a serious fungal infection that primarily affects immunocompromised patients.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiology of invasive aspergillosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aflatoxin production causing direct tissue damage","Macrophage destruction by fungal proteases","Neutrophil hyperactivity leading to excessive inflammation","Allergic response to \u03b2-1,3-glucan in fungal cell walls","Germination of conidia into tissue-invasive hyphae"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pathophysiology of invasive aspergillosis primarily involves \u003Cstrong\u003Egermination of conidia into tissue-invasive hyphae\u003C/strong\u003E. In immunocompromised hosts, particularly those with neutropenia, inhaled \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus\u003C/em\u003E conidia (2-3 \u00b5m in size) reach the alveoli and are not effectively cleared by the immune system. These conidia then germinate into hyphae that can invade blood vessels and surrounding tissues, causing tissue necrosis and potentially disseminating to other organs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAflatoxin production causing direct tissue damage\u003C/strong\u003E - While \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus\u003C/em\u003E species can produce aflatoxin when growing on crops like corn and peanuts, aflatoxin is primarily associated with hepatotoxicity and increased liver cancer risk when ingested, not with invasive pulmonary aspergillosis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeutrophil hyperactivity leading to excessive inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E - Invasive aspergillosis is actually associated with neutropenia and impaired neutrophil function. Neutrophils are protective against \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus\u003C/em\u003E by producing reactive oxygen intermediates that kill hyphae.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllergic response to \u03b2-1,3-glucan in fungal cell walls\u003C/strong\u003E - \u03b2-1,3-glucan is recognised by dectin-1 receptors on macrophages as part of the normal immune response to \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus\u003C/em\u003E. Allergic responses to \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus\u003C/em\u003E cause different clinical entities like allergic bronchopulmonary aspergillosis, not invasive disease.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMacrophage destruction by fungal proteases\u003C/strong\u003E - While \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus\u003C/em\u003E does produce proteases, the primary issue in invasive aspergillosis is not macrophage destruction but rather the inability of neutrophils and macrophages to control fungal growth due to immunosuppression.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pathogenesis of invasive aspergillosis depends on both the immunocompromised state of the host (particularly neutropenia) and the virulence factors of \u003Cem\u003EAspergillus\u003C/em\u003E, including its ability to germinate into invasive hyphae, produce antioxidants that counter host defences, and express adhesins that facilitate tissue invasion.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aspergillus species are transmitted as airborne conidia that can reach alveoli due to their small size (2-3 \u00b5m).","Alveolar macrophages recognise Aspergillus through TLR2 and dectin-1 receptors, which detect \u03b2-1,3-glucan in the fungal cell wall.","Neutrophils are critical for defence against Aspergillus by producing reactive oxygen intermediates that kill fungal hyphae.","Aspergillus produces virulence factors including adhesins, antioxidants (e.g., catalases), enzymes, and toxins."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; page 387."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79981"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20817"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79981"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-06T13:01:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-06T13:02:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13692"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97366"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https:/